<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-407-570  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 407 570.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 3 1989 v6 n26 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sikes gets Bush nod to fill top FCC post. (first task to setnational telecommunications policy goals) (Alfred Sikes) (FederalCommunications Commission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Alfred Sikes has been nominated by President Bush to fill the postof chairman of the FCC.andP;  He currently serves as assistantsecretary for communications and information in the CommerceDepartment and administrator of the National Telecommunicationsand Information Administration (NTIA).andP;  Sikes' appointment hasbeen the subject of speculation since Feb 1989.andP;  His first goal aschairman would be evaluation of the telecommunications industryand setting national policy priorities.andP;  He says that definitenational goals would ease regulatory gridlock between the FCC andCongress.andP;  A proponent of both communications industry price capsand deregulation, Sikes feels that the agency has expended to muchenergy on telephone service rather than evaluation of newtechnologies and how they can be used to make the US morecompetitive.andP;  Sikes would focus the agency's attention on theglobal implications of its decisions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionTelecommunicationsPolitical IssuesChairmenNew AppointmentGovernment Agency.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Sikes, Alfred (selection and appointment).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>